<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06363040 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06363040 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  HIGH-SCHOOL; BASKETBALL; GAME; RESULT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Non-league games are a time of self-discovery for high school teams.;   Withthat being the case, Washington (8-2) discovered something it didn'tnecessarily want to learn in the first round of the Milpitas Classic on Fridaynight.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  LEIGH STIFLES LEGAN, DEFEATS WASHINGTON  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  High School; Roundup  </MEMO><TEXT>     When Chuck Legan, the Huskies' top scorer, doesn't get on track, neitherdoes Washington.;   Leigh stifled Legan, and the Longhorns (9-1) went on to a55-45 win, avenging the season-ending loss Leigh suffered against the Huskiesin the first round of last season's Northern California Division IIIplayoffs.;   In the second game Friday night, Dieu Vuong scored 20 points --nine on three-pointers -- to lead Milpitas to a 68-59 victory over PiedmontHills (4-7). The Trojans (8-1) will play Leigh for the title today at 8 p.m.;  Like last season's Leigh-Washington game, Friday's was an emotional tug ofwar.;   &quot;Defensively, the kids were up to the task on that,&quot; Leigh Coach RogerSmith said. &quot;We told them they had to do it defensively if they wanted to winit tonight.&quot;;   The Longhorns followed orders.;   Legan, who scored 29 pointsin the Huskies' 70-62 win over Hayward last Saturday, scored only 10 points.;  Leigh, meanwhile, got big performances from Marc Mirizzi and Joe Cattolico.;  Mirizzi scored 19 points, including three three-pointers, and Cattolicoscored 15, seven in the second period when the Longhorns built a nine-pointlead.;   That lead swelled to 42-28 with about two minutes left in the thirdquarter, but the Huskies rallied.;   That rally started in the fourth quarterwhen Mirizzi was called for a charge that angered the Washington players.;  Both teams had been exchanging verbal jabs after hard fouls, and Mirizzi'scharge stirred things up further.;   Leigh's fans and the Washington benchhowled.;   So did Smith, who was off the bench arguing calls most of thegame.;   His team was just as verbal on the court, but Smith said that didn'tbother him.;   &quot;Basically, this is a quiet team,&quot; he said. &quot;I'm trying to getthem to talk some more.&quot;;   After Mirizzi's charge, though, Steve Glocksilenced some of that talk with a three-pointer that cut Leigh's lead to 48-42with 3 minutes, 47 seconds left.;   Washington, however, got no closer.;  Legan stole the ball on Leigh's next possession, but Joachim Peats wasn't ableto make the field goal that would have cut the lead to four.;   And, afterboth teams missed the front ends of one-and-one free-throw situations, ScottDobrenz made a free throw that put the Longhorns up 49-42 with 2:35 left.;  Two free throws by Mirizzi at the 2:01 mark put Leigh back in control at51-42.; OTHER GAMES: Aaron Heil scored 30 points, but Fremont (6-6) was beaten71-54 by University (Irvine) 71-54 in the St. Francis Holiday boys' basketballtournament. University (5-7) jumped to a 17-0 lead. In other HolidayTournament games, St. Francis' Al Morton scored 27 points, but the Lancers(7-3) were beaten 59-54 by Palo Alto (8-1); Malcolm Davies scored 15 pointsfor Homestead (5-7), but the Mustangs were routed 76-39 by Mount Eden (9-1);and San Ramon Valley (8-2) topped San Luis Obispo (5-4). . . . In girls'basketball, Michelle Wagner scored 26 points to lead Lynbrook (6-1) to a 54-43victory over Harbor (10-2) in the Mitty-Cupertino Tournament.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  WAYNE WASHINGTON, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911228  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  December  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  581  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday, December 28, 199100363040,SJ